        <h2>
         <a href="http://myorifankle.com/2015/09/6-months-post-injury-update/">
          6 months post injury update
         </a>
        </h2>
       </header>
      </article>
     </section>
     <section class="postText">
     </section>
     <p>
      Hard to believe, but it has now been 6 months since I broke my ankle. It‚Äôs definitely time for an update!
     </p>
     <p>
      But first, a quick run-down on how our trip to Bulgaria was ankle-wise (this trip happened at about the 4-1/2 month mark). I‚Äôm copying part of this from my reply to a commenter on a previous post since it already explains how things went.
     </p>
     <p>
      To be honest, the trip was a lot tougher than I thought it would be, mainly due to the swelling. I‚Äôve never seen my foot so big. Actually, they were both huge. My calves were hard as a rock and I couldn‚Äôt even feel my kneecaps. I blew out one of my sandal straps from the pressure against it. So I had to buy a really loose pair of flip-flops because I couldn‚Äôt get anything else on.
     </p>
     <p>
      It was pretty painful too. We did lots of walking and we were gone for full days, so I was only able to put my foot up when I went to bed. And it wasn‚Äôt enough to bring the swelling down to normal by morning. So each day my feet were a little bigger and a little more painful.
     </p>
     <p>
      Obviously, I had been overly optimistic about my readiness for the trip, but it was worth it. And I‚Äôm extremely grateful that I didn‚Äôt re-injure myself while there. The sidewalks in Bulgaria leave a bit to be desired; here‚Äôs what many of them look like:
     </p>
     <p>
      <a href="http://myorifankle.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/image85.jpg">
       <img width="300" height="200" alt="image85" src="http://myorifankle.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/image85-300x200.jpg" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-185" />
      </a>
     </p>
     <p>
      And the European women walk around in their sky-high heels on this stuff without even looking down!
     </p>
     <p>
      So overall, it didn‚Äôt go as well as I‚Äôd hoped but it didn‚Äôt keep me from having a good time. I had my pain pills with me and was able to get by with one per day because I didn‚Äôt have many left. I ignored the pain as best I could and just soaked up the experience.
      <img style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" class="wp-smiley" alt=":)" src="http://myorifankle.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/simple-smile.png" />
     </p>
     <p>
      One benefit of the trip, though, is that when we got back and the swelling went down, I found my range of motion had improved rather significantly. I think it was like a week of intense physical therapy over there, with all that I was asking of my ankle on a daily basis!
     </p>
     <h3>
      As for now‚Ä¶
     </h3>
     <p>
      Now, at the 6-month mark, I feel like my recovery has stalled a bit. I‚Äôm getting around with sufficient function to do everyday tasks. But I‚Äôm not progressing the way I‚Äôd like. There‚Äôs more pain than there was before the trip, but maybe that‚Äôs because I‚Äôm stretching and exercising it more. I hope that‚Äôs all it is. I don‚Äôt really think anything is wrong; I‚Äôm just impatient.
     </p>
     <p>
      When I get up in the morning, it‚Äôs still pretty stiff. Of course, my whole body is, since I‚Äôm over the hill! But I have to go down the stairs one at a time, step-together, step-together, until it loosens up.
     </p>
     <p>
      I‚Äôm still getting shooting pains from time to time, although that‚Äôs getting more infrequent, thank goodness. After I‚Äôve been on my feet a while, especially if I‚Äôm doing housework or have been walking around a lot, my heel and inner ankle get quite sore.
     </p>
     <p>
      Range of motion is probably 80-90% of normal if I really stretch it, but that doesn‚Äôt come without some pain. And it still swells considerably by mid-day and into the evening, which still frustrates me. I just can‚Äôt sit with my feet up very much if I want to make a living!
     </p>
     <p>
      So all in all, I guess I‚Äôm still progressing, albeit slowly. At least I can do most of my normal activities. There are a lot of people a lot worse off than me for a million different reasons, so I am grateful and try to focus on the positives.
     </p>
     <p>
      I‚Äôll update again in a couple months or so or if anything new develops.
     </p>
     <div class="sidebadge">
