        <div class="text">
         <p>
          This was a great post. I am four months post op (11screws and a plate)‚Ä¶ And I alternate between feeling like I‚Äôm making great progress and thinking I am not.  But it all feels normal. It‚Äôs a slowwwww process, isn‚Äôt it?
          <br />
          PT is essential!
         </p>
         <p>
          During my 8.5 weeks NWB I found only a couple of sites that had good information (yours is one)‚Ä¶ There are so many horror stories out there that it was hard to get a good idea of what most people experience.
         </p>
         <p>
          I half expected my screws to shoot out like bullets with every step!!!
          <img draggable="false" class="emoji" alt="üòâ" src="http://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/72x72/1f609.png" />
          <br />
          I had never been injured and was nervous about every pain while in the cast, but there wasn‚Äôt good information out there about that part, except the extremes‚Ä¶ And non compliants‚Ä¶
         </p>
         <p>
          If I could offer any advice to others it would be DO YOUR EXERCISES! Do arms, weight, resistance band‚Ä¶ Your arms and wrists get tired and sore. Ask your doc for appropriate NWB exercises‚Ä¶ Heck you have the time
          <img draggable="false" class="emoji" alt="üòâ" src="http://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/72x72/1f609.png" />
         </p>
         <p>
          Do toe and leg raises on the unaffected foot! As you are released to weight bearing or as your surgeon gives exercises‚Ä¶. Do them!! Faithfully!! ‚Ä¶ I was told about atrophy but boy I didn‚Äôt realize!!!
         </p>
         <p>
          There should be a one page with bullet points somewhere for during healing, easing into weight bearing and post!
         </p>
         <p>
          Btw how is your balance? Do you use assistive devices? Did u on your trip?
          <br />
          Do you wear a brace? Can you jog or walk briskly?
         </p>
        </div>
        <div class="reply">
        </div>
