      <li id="li-comment-127" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 clearfix">
       <img width="38" height="38" class="avatar avatar-38 photo" srcset="http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/4b1e91eac6b260acaa8b8db548829363?s=76&d=mm&r=g 2x" src="http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/4b1e91eac6b260acaa8b8db548829363?s=38&d=mm&r=g" alt="" />
       <div id="comment-127">
        <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
         <strong>
          Mell
         </strong>
         <span>
          October 4, 2015 at 11:30 am
         </span>
        </div>
        <div class="text">
         <p>
          Ps I didn‚Äôt realize you didn‚Äôt go the PT route‚Ä¶ Sound like it‚Äôs going well without‚Ä¶ I‚Äôve read that for others too. But as you said ‚Ä¶ Movement and exercises are essential!
          <br />
          For me, and for folks considering whether or not to go: my injury was kind of a freak thing during everyday activity so I have a lot of fear of regular life activity. PT is actually helping me with my confidence.
          <br />
          PT helps strengthen the stabilizers in the ankle..
          <br />
          But they also help you learn to mimic awkward balance and walking situations in a controlled and safe environment. If your ankle is locked up tight they manually help to loosen it up‚Ä¶ And the education around the anatomy of the injury, tissue and healing is great.
         </p>
        </div>
        <div class="reply">
        </div>
       </div>
      </li>
