         </span>
        </div>
        <div class="text">
         <p>
          Thank you for your posts!
          <img style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" class="wp-smiley" alt=":)" src="http://myorifankle.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/simple-smile.png" />
          You know, I didn‚Äôt INTEND to drop out of PT, lol. I do believe it‚Äôs important, and I know it sounds lame to say I was too busy. But this honestly happened at a time when I had so many irons in the fire I just couldn‚Äôt bring myself to go there when I was already stressing my ankle to its limits and probably beyond. I have been doing some of the exercises they showed me at home, but I will admit it‚Äôs often hit and miss. However, I do A LOT of ankle circles and flexion and extension as I watch TV or whatever to increase my range of motion. So even though it hasn‚Äôt been against resistance, I‚Äôm sure that‚Äôs been helping quite a bit.
         </p>
         <p>
          Now, because I feel like my progress has stalled somewhat, I‚Äôm wondering if I should go back to PT since my life has now calmed down and I have more time. I suppose it‚Äôs not too late. Of course, the other consideration is whether my insurance will help me out with the cost, but I can look into that.
         </p>
         <p>
          It‚Äôs funny you mentioned how it was a freak accident for you because it was for me too. That is hard to deal with, isn‚Äôt it, because we can‚Äôt just say, ‚ÄúWell, learned my lesson, I‚Äôm never going skydiving again!‚Äù LOL. I can‚Äôt stop using stairs just because I stepped off the last one in just the wrong way that it broke bones! So I‚Äôm fearful too that it could happen again.
         </p>
        </div>
